# Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002

The **Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002** (Pub.L. 107–171, 116 Stat. 134, enacted May 13, 2002), also known as the **2002 U.S. Farm Bill** or the **Agricultural Act of 2001**, is a comprehensive piece of [United States federal law](/United_States_federal_law) that governed [agricultural policy](/Agricultural_policy_of_the_United_States) from 2002 to 2007. This legislation, which was enacted by the [107th United States Congress](/107th_United_States_Congress) and signed into law by President [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush), allocated approximately $16.5 billion annually toward [agricultural subsidies](/Agricultural_subsidies), significantly impacting the production of grains, oilseeds, and upland cotton. The act was notable for its timing, as it was debated and passed in the aftermath of the [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks), which added a layer of complexity to its legislative journey.

The Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002 was structured into ten titles, each addressing distinct aspects of [agriculture](/Agriculture), [ecology](/Ecology), [energy](/Energy), [trade](/Trade), and [nutrition](/Nutrition). This act was later superseded by the [2007 U.S. Farm Bill](/2007_U.S._Farm_Bill), but its provisions and the debates surrounding its passage remain significant in understanding the evolution of U.S. agricultural policy.

## Legislative History

The legislative journey of the Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002 was marked by intense debate and significant amendments. The bill was introduced in the [House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) as H.R. 2646 by [Larry Combest](/Larry_Combest) (R-TX) on July 26, 2001. It was considered by the [House Committee on Agriculture](/United_States_House_Committee_on_Agriculture) and the [House Committee on International Relations](/United_States_House_Committee_on_Foreign_Affairs) before being passed by the House on October 5, 2001, with a vote of 291–120.

The Senate passed its version of the bill, titled the Agriculture, Conservation, and Rural Enhancement Act of 2002, on February 13, 2002, with a vote of 58–40. The differences between the House and Senate versions led to a series of negotiations, culminating in a joint conference committee report on May 1, 2002. The House agreed to the conference report on May 2, 2002, with a vote of 280–141, and the Senate followed on May 8, 2002, with a vote of 64–35. President George W. Bush signed the bill into law on May 13, 2002.

## Summary

The Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002 included a wide range of provisions aimed at supporting various aspects of agriculture and rural development. One of the notable provisions was the implementation of [country-of-origin labeling](/Mandatory_country-of-origin_labeling_of_food_sold_in_the_United_States) for fresh beef, pork, and lamb. This provision was intended to provide consumers with more information about the origin of their food, thereby promoting transparency and potentially supporting domestic producers.

